od, criminality, citizenship, and legality. Fukushima examines how migrants legally cross into visibility, through frames of citizenship, and narratives of victimhood. She explores the interdisciplinary framing of the role of the law and the legal system, the notion of "perfect victimhood", and iconic victims, and how trafficking subjects are resurrected for contemporary movements as illustrated in visuals, discourse, court records, and policy. Migrant Crossings deeply interrogates what it means to bear witness to migration in these migratory times—and what such migrant crossings mean for subjects who experience violence during or after their crossing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aForeign workers, AsianxAbuse ofzUnited States. 0aForeign workers, Latin AmericanxAbuse ofzUnited States. 0aHuman trafficking victimszUnited States. 0aHuman traffickingzUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxAbuse ofzUnited States. 7aLAW / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aAsian.  aLatina/o.  adecolonial praxis.  ahuman trafficking.  aimmigration.  alaw.  atransdisciplinary.  atransnational feminism.  awitnessing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020 Englishz978311070486008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020z9783110704587oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360950140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503609501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503609501.jpg  a978-3